,Recommended,297750,35000511,Posted: 16 September,all,Badgerspin,"Despite what others have to say, I think this is a pretty solid CC game. It's not as good as Invasion Normandy (which, IMHO, is one of the best games I've ever played), but it's still enjoyable. I'd recommend it to fans of the CC series. If you're new to the series, I'd wait until this goes on sale.I agree though that the pricetag is hard to justify. I guarantee that the reviews for this game would notably go up if they dropped the price by $10 - $15. I doubt the same amount of resources that go into a AAA title (or a fresh indie) went into this game; espeically given that most of the aspects of the game (and probably large swaths of the code) already existed and weren't built up from scratch. (It would be interesting to see the source code for CC:V and compare it to this one.)I know others have complained about the lack of graphics updates, but I'm happy they didn't change any of that. That's essentially what makes a CC game feel like a CC game. If it ain't broke, don't fix it.Playing as the British, it is HARD. (For me, that's part of the appeal.) It reminds me a lot of Battle of the Bulge in the early missions playing as the Allies; where you take it up the rump from the Germans on a regular basis. I feel like that's an ok comparison to the difficulty? The Germans primarily have Tiger and Panther tanks, which presents its own set of challenges. These things are BEASTS and extremely difficult to take out. (Moreso than in the other installments.) Volley fire from the flanks with multiple anti-tank troops is the better method if you don't have any tanks. If you do have tanks, going head on isn't going to work out very well for you... The front armor on Tigers feels somewhat impervious. (Which... Is kind of how it was in reality.) As always, the allied tanks feel like they're made of the finest Chinesium.This part will sound like complaints (one part definitely is), but they're just something to be aware of for those who have played previous CC games.There's been some changes in the AI. Just like all other CC games, the tanks never really go where you want them to. Now, they'll randomly try to punch through a hedgerow and get tracked when a road was right next to them. Your drivers are idiots, but now they're even bigger idiots. With commands, there's a lag time that wasn't there before. Your troops may or may not take their sweet time getting somewhere when you tell them to move fast. They've pretty obviously nerfed mortars, but I think in Invasion Normandy they were a bit overpowered. (the 60mm's definitely were.) Now they're closer to what they were in Battle of the Bulge. However, they also seem to be less accurate now as well. Not that they were ever overly accurate, but you'll be able to tell a difference from previous installments.My biggest complaint about the game is that the customization of the units you can deploy isn't there anymore. With Invasion Normandy, this was my favorite aspect. I'm surprised they didn't keep that in. Instead, your bound to what is a mostly confusing system of what you can and can't switch around. It's a bit... Obnoxious? I don't really see the point of this change."
